  ee        = {http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-28717-6_14},
  year      = {2012},
  isbn      = {978-3-642-28716-9},
  ee        = {http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-28717-6}
}

*** Comments:
+ Goal: Compile Isabelle Specifications to executable generators (enumerators)
+++ Their notion of size is either wrong or VERY weird. Int lists of size 5
can't have "big" elements in the tails.. Almost like decreasing lists.
+ Aim to combine fast execution with concrete values and avoid symmetric
  executions as in narrowing.
+ Allows negation assuming the Horn Clauses are stratified.
+ Sound underapproximation of predicates.
+ Converts n-ary functions to (n+1)-ary predicates via flattening
+ Imprecise mode analysis (exist better), don't care because "they always get
  a generator"
+ Mode analysis and consistency allows/gives serialization of generation
+ Reasonable heuristics for local choices in their mode analysis 
  ++ minimize missing values 
    -> Partly recover mode consistency
  ++ predicates derived from functions used to compute result
    -> Avoid useless enumeration where computation could work
  ++ use preds and modes that don't need generators 
    -> Obscure reason - not clear!
  ++ minimize output positions 
    -> Choose Q x (i => bool) instead of P x y (i => o => bool)
  ++ prefer recursion
    -> P xs -> C xs -> P (x::xs) :=> prefer P for generation (bottom up)
 + Three different evaluation monads. 
  - One for unbounded computations (not used?)
  - Positive contexts : 
   -- Carrier is : int -> a cps 
   -- bind+ xq f = (\i. if i = 0 then empty else bind+ (xq (i-1)) (\a. f a i))
     -> Empty if depth-limit reached
     -> Otherwise decreased depth limit to its argument
  - Negative contexts :
   -- Change carrier type to int -> a option cps where None signifies reaching
    the depth limit to distinguish depth-limit + failure. (3-valued logic)
 + As in quickCheck, use typeclass for gen (enumeratable) types
 + Comparison with exhaustive and narrowing is favorable (to be expected)
 + No comparison with other "smart" things (eg. manual generators)
 + Case study based on very small mutation testing
   
