  biburl    = {http://dblp.uni-trier.de/rec/bib/journals/jfp/ClaessenDP15},
  bibsource = {dblp computer science bibliography, http://dblp.org}
}

*** Comments
+ Goal: Automatically derive generators from predicate / Boolean functions
+ Representation of ADTs that allows indexing based on FEAT ideas
+ Generating values of specific size 
+ GADT representation of ADT spaces as sums and products. Adds cost to
  constructors and allows "map"
+ Predicate guided indexing exploits laziness to refine generation. 
  They index into a "predicate space" refining things that are uneeded
  structurally. 
+ This indexing leads to problems with products and sizes. They do a
  transformation of products in terms of other constructs in their Space GADT.
  Extra care is taken not to skew the generation with repect to left/right
  pairs of elements.
+ They pick an index, try to generate that term, and then try to generate 
  then "next" index until they reach a bound. Bound = 0 means complete
  uniformity. Bound = infinite means completely skewed. In between there is 
  a hybrid algorithm with some uniformity guarantees in terms of how skewed
  the distribution is.
+ Optimization: Parallel operations for short-circuiting conjunctions
+ Compared to SmallCheck, this uses size instead of depth and uses randomness
  instead of enumeration. Compared to FEAT, they handle complex ADT
  invariants. 
+ This feels like it combines a neat FEAT idea with the narrowing strategies 
  of SmallCheck ets in a random setting. But it seems to work quite well!
