*** bib
@inproceedings{PalkaAST11,
 author = {Pa{\l}ka, Micha{\l} H. and Claessen, Koen and Russo, Alejandro and Hughes, John},
 title = {Testing an Optimising Compiler by Generating Random Lambda Terms},
 booktitle = {Proceedings of the 6th International Workshop on Automation of Software Test},
 shortbooktitle = {AST},
 series = {AST '11},
 year = {2011},
 isbn = {978-1-4503-0592-1},
 location = {Waikiki, Honolulu, HI, USA},
 pages = {91--97},
 numpages = {7},
 url = {http://doi.acm.org/10.1145/1982595.1982615},
 doi = {10.1145/1982595.1982615},
 acmid = {1982615},
 publisher = {ACM},
 address = {New York, NY, USA},
 keywords = {random testing, software testing},
 } 
*** Comments
+ Goal 1: Generate random well-typed lambda terms for STLC 
+ Goal 2: Use these to find bugs in GHC

+ Starts with a naive approach: 
  - Flip all typing rules into generation rules. Given a type
    you use the typing rules to generate well typed things
    based on the premises of the rule. 
  - The App rule is problematic - it creates a type out of 
    thin air. This type could lead to dead ends/infinite loops. 
    To counter it they use backtracking and size bounds.
+ Refine the approach by using an INDIR rule. If there exists 
  a function constant with the require result, they use that 
  constant's type to make progress.
+ Polymorphism is an extra problem, generalization of the App issue.
  (Imagine app :: \αβ (α->β) -> α -> β)
  - Solution was to only generate types that "can" be reached from 
    function constants based on a simple reachability argument.
+ Optimize distributions to limit backtracking at the cost of 
  low chances of generating "weird"/"complex" terms.
+ They seed this generation with Haskell's Prelude and do 
  differential testing on the optimizer. They revealed a couple of 
  bugs (not too interesting as bugs IMO - throwing away seqs).
+ Minimal reference to shrinking (thesis has a lot more)

