** TODO GADT enumeration [Yakushev10]
*** bib
@incollection{Yakushev10,
  year={2010},
  isbn={978-3-642-11930-9},
  booktitle={Approaches and Applications of Inductive Programming},
  volume={5812},
  series={Lecture Notes in Computer Science},
  editor={Schmid, Ute and Kitzelmann, Emanuel and Plasmeijer, Rinus},
  doi={10.1007/978-3-642-11931-6_5},
  title={Enumerating Well-Typed Terms Generically},
  url={http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-11931-6_5},
  publisher={Springer Berlin Heidelberg},
  author={Rodriguez Yakushev, Alexey and Jeuring, Johan},
  pages={93-116},
  language={English}
}
*** Comments
+ Aimed at enumeration given a type
+ Uses GADTs to do generic programming in Haskell
+ Extends the idea of a spine view:
  - GADT describing a single value of an ADT in Haskell
  - TypeSpine describes the constructor structure (for read, etc)
+ Existentially quantified types cause a problem 
  - The constructor in which it occurs must have a representation
    for it, otherwise the spine view can't handle it
  - EApp :: Expr (a -> b) -> Expr a -> Expr b
    toSpine (Expr b) (Expr fun args) = ...  *no a*
+ Solution: 
  - Extend spine view with constructor representing existential 
    quantification
+ For lambda terms, represent the lambda expressions as a GADT, 
  convert them to spine view and perform a BFS search on the 
  generic representation 
  - They don't add arithmetic constants or recursion in their language
    although they claim "we could"
  - The "cool" thing is that they get typed terms "for free" since the 
    enumeration is done on the constrained GADT space. 
  - No performance evaluation because they believe "it is the slowest"
            
