*** Comments
+ Generate random Erlang programs to test refactoring tools
+ Custom generators make use of *attribute grammars*
+ Erlang's syntax and static semantics can be described using 
  *L-attribute grammars* and the authors created a random 
  generator for such grammars
+ In L-attribute grammars a single symbol in a rule may depened 
  on attributes only to its left
+ The authors allow the user to seperate different parts in a generation 
  rule in some form of "staging" or delayed binding
  - They allow arbitrary erlang code to manipulate attributes after 
    each such "stage"
  - Special handling of recursion allowing fixed size (vector style) or 
    random size (list style)
  - Allows for frequencies in grammar rule alternatives
+ They create Erlang Syntax trees in a bottom up fashion
+ This is a DSL for generators in a specific setting that could be 
  applied to a lot of different cases! Very interesting! 
- Erlang is untyped, so there is no mention of using type information
  to make things *behave better*, although it is probably worth it to 
  test the behavior of the refactoring engines on non-well-typed but 
  allowed inputs.
- Allowed inputs for testing after program generation generated using
  the success typings of Dialyzer
