*** Comments
+ Intro/Abstract claims obvious improvement against naive generation, 
  worse than Palka hand-written one
+ Example seems to follow closely on the ideas present in Palka paper, only
  for a more generically specified type-system

+ Rewrites programs consisting of metafunctions and judgement forms into the
  set of possible derivations they can generate.
+ Randomness + Heuristics to select a derviation
+ Based on CLP

+ Each program is a set of definitions, which is in turn a set of inference
  rules written in a specific format. In the rules the conclusion is always 
  a named pattern or a disequality constraints.
+ Sequences that ultimately lead to failure cause backtracking

+ To compile metafunctions to sets of inference clauses, they add disequality
  constraints to impose ordering. (disequlity between all previous clauses in 
  the metafunction)

+ Constraint store is idempotent as a substitution 
+ Invariant: Always satisfiable
+ Incremental solving of constraints:
  - Given a constraint store and a new equality constraint
  - Apply the constraint store (EQ part) as a substitution and then 
    do syntactic unification
  - Then check for consistency
+ For dissolve: 
  - Again substitute the equality part
  - Try to *disunify*
    - Always disunified -> no need to add constraint
    - Always unified    -> inconsistent disequality
    - Otherwise add the disequality
  - Solve disunification by DeMorganizing (negation is conjunction of
    equalities, solve by unification)

+ Search Heuristics
  - Need to collect all choices that can fire
  - Random permutation of those and chooses one.
  - If it fails backtrack to the next choice
  (This algorithm IS the Palka algorithm for picking derivations)
+ Depth Bound to limit productions
  - Twist: after limit is reached try to finish off the derivation quickly
  - Doesn't specify what happens in "infinite" derivations (I assume there
    also exists a *hard* limit)    
+ Permutation matters:
  - Prefer rules with more premises near the beginning of the derivation
  - Prefer fewer later on
+ Also can use uniform permutations
+ Complementary approaches - decide between the two randomly in the beginning


+ Richer model extension
  - Largely based on matches and mismatches
  - Interesting choices for choosing variables (eg. variable-not-mentioned,
    etc)
  - For non-terminals there exists no efficient algorithm for intersection
    -> Conservative check at unification time

+ Clearly more efficient than naive generation, practically across the board
  - Limitations: 
    - Using racket code that their generator can't handle
    - No type system at all in a model
    - No ellipses/Kleene Star
  - They excluded a benchmark because of termination issues 
+ They use the Palka generator at sizes 50/70/90 yet their own with depths
  6/7/8/10? The notion of size/depth seems to be the same in both, with the
  exception that after the limit is reached they "continue" the derivation
  with smaller rules
+ Also do the "polymorphic constants in the environment trick" to stay
  competitive

