*** Comments:
+ First paper 
  - Very early work
  - More like a "We have a QC-like thing in Focal"
  - Only not as customizable as QC... (And the automation lacks)
   + ML like language
   + *species* look like abstract modules that allow inheritance
   + *collections* are the implementation of species
   + No existentials in properties
   + Prenex normal form
   + Rewrite all dysjunctions/conjunctions so 
     that the final form is a bunch of 
     a1 => a2 => ... => an => b 
   + Negation only allowed in the leaf level
   + Generate-and-test approach
   + For generating recursive ADTs they choose recursive/non-recursive 
     with 1/2 probability and then select amongst the families. This 
     should lead to very small test cases in cases like lists and 
     infinite generation for tree-like structures. 
   + Experimentation is minimal (10 valid test cases, some times they got as many as
     1000 discards). 10 mutants introduced (7 killed, 1 showed stupid int
     domain (1-10) and 2 had UNSAT precs). Not much of an experimentation in
     this...
   + They prove a theorem about preservation of pre-domains which seems rather
     obvious: Their rewrite system allows for testing the elementary properties 
     seperately (although I'm not sure that is a good idea with their discards) 
   + They calculate MC/DC coverage based on 10! tests...
+ Second paper: 
  + Goal : Automatically generate test data that satisfy MC/DC coverage for 
    preconditions using constraint reasoning
  + MC/DC for precondition just means that we have to generate something that
    satisfies the entire precondition once, something that falsifies it once 
    and to ensure that each individual atom influences the truth value of 
    the precondition. Not that hard... it requires n+1 tests where n is the 
    number of /\-ed precs.. 
  + Large part of the paper deals with the translation of Focal to miniFocal
    (simpler IR) and then from MiniFocal to clp(FD), which allows them to use 
    constraint logic programing techniques to generate test data. 
  + The constraint solving aspect uses two techniques: constraint propagation 
    and labeling. Labeling is the equivalent of our *make choice* operator
    while the constraint propagation is the moral equivalent of our refine
    loop. 
  + They have partial correctness and completeness, although they claim that 
    "completeness might not be indispensible" for efficiency reasons
  + CLP solver they use is SICStus Prolog.
  + Experimenting with generating 10 MC/DC compliant test suites. Compared to
    naive approaches they clearly outperform them, although MC/DC is not such
    an impressive accomplishment (QC takes 48 secs for an AVL tree by
    generating random Trees!)
+ Third paper is exactly the same as the second one, with different style and
  minor representation changes.
    
