*** Comments
+ Goal: Euclide, a CBT tool for critical C programs
+ Three distinct (but-not-so-distinct) applications:
  - Structural Data Generation (for Testing)
  - Counterexample Generation  (Constraint Solving to find bugs)
  - Partial Program Proving    (Absence of errors in bounded finite domains)
+ Handles a (reasonable) subset of C, excluding things like recusion and 
  dynamic memory alloc) 
+ Approach based on transforming programs into a dedicated constraint
  language, using a series of passes
  - Normalization - decompose complex statements/simplifications
  - Points-to analysis 
  - SSA 
  - Constraint generation 
+ Solving by:
  - Constraint propagation. This is similar in spirit to arc consistency and
    our refine function. It amounts to domain filtering with some possible
    approximations
  - Dynamic Linear Relaxations. Interesting idea, overapproximating
    constraints with linear ones. For example, an if-then-else representation 
    with the union of a then and the else branch. TODO: Look at [DenmatGD07] for
    more on this.
  - Different heuristics for search: 
    ! Domain splitting (similar to Benjamin's idea for making choices not
    actually make a choice but just reduce ranges for instance)
    ! Exhaustive Search
    ! Randomness 
+ Implementation uses Prolog heavily (Sicstus again!) 
+ Big Case Study in Aviation software. Found a bug not already present in 
  literature
    
