  bibsource = {dblp computer science bibliography, http://dblp.org}
}
*** Comments
!! Much better intro to probabilistic programming than the Milch papers
+ They define Church, a lisp-like language with added probabilistic semantics
+ Write μ(e, env) probability distribution that (eval e env) results in,
  given that e is *admissible*. 
+ Admissibility for e means termination of evaluation, meaning that all the
  evaluation histories (products of each random choice during its evaluation)
  sum to 1
+ Basic operations are *queries*
  - (query 'e p env) is a procedure which samples from μ('e, env) with the
    added condition that p evaluates to true
  - Querying is effectively sampling from a precondition! 
  ++ EXAMPLE: 
  (query '(pair flip flip) (lambda (v) (+ (first v) (last v))))
  Describes the conditional distribution of two flips, given that at least 
  one of them lands heads (+ > 0)
+ Support for lexicalizing queries (naming sets of random values used for
  evaluation)
+ Memoization is VERY different in this context.
  - Memoizing a value changes the semantics (obviously, sampling is a side
    effect after all in an IO/Gen like monad for random number generation)
  - Instead of always memoizing (resulting in "repeated" contexts) or not,
    we can randomize whether we memoize or not. (Dirichlet processes choose 
    from distributions).
+ Exchangability is the generalization of purity (distributions invariant
  under execution order)
+ Implement mem using something like "lazy memoization" to avoid the infinity
  problem 
+ Rejection sampling can lead to intractable queries (ie. generate-and-filter
  doesn't work...)
+ They mention something called *collapsed rejection sampling* as an
  improvement upon generate-and-test, BUT they say that leads to intractable
  queries as well AND I couldn't find any reference.
+ TODO: Lookup *collapsed rejection sampling*
+ Actual Sampling Algorithm: Markov Chain Monte Carlo like
  - Based on computation histories 
  - They record (in a tree structure) ALL the random choices during an
    execution
  - Pick one choice at random, change it with respect to some Markov kernel
    and update the history following that change.
  - After making the change, the algorithm accepts or rejects it based on the 
    Metropolis-Hastings criterion (by checking if it is in a "more probable" 
    region based on an approximation). The authors themselves state that this
    is handwaivy. 
  - The basic comparison with random test generation is that this is
    effectively backtracking, only making a different choice at ANY change in
    the past (instead of last - DFS or first - throw everything
    away/BFS). Interesting idea.
+ Still, their query is "still inefficient for most machine learning
  applications"
