}
*** Comments
+ Probabilistic Logic Programming
+ ProbLog transforms queries to DNFs 
+ The problem of infering the probability of a query in DNF is #P-complete
+ Other probabilistic logic implementations either impose restrictions or 
don't scale to larger ides
+ Two methods of dealing with this:
  - Program Sampling (standard MC/MC sampling, only applied to ProbLog)
  - DNF sampling (their contribution)
+ DNF sampling:
  - Program sampling suffers from the same issue as rejection sampling in 
    testing. Too many failing derivations in the SLD tree <-> too many
    generated tests don't satisfy preconditions
  - Associate worlds to conjuncts (1st conjunct that it supports)
  - Sample for a specific conjunct by setting the conjunct and randomly 
    the rest of the variables 
  - Accept it only for the worlds that are "good" with its associated worlds
    (this informally "breaks" the non-independence of the sums)
  - Not always easy to generate the DNF for a query for large instances though
+ Comparison with program sampling:
  - Very good when mutually exclusive samples
  - Worse than PS when not
