** DONE Importance Sampling [Pfeffer2007b]
*** bib
@techreport{Pfeffer2007b,
  author = {Avi Pfeffer},
  title  = { A general importance sampling
             algorithm for probabilistic programs},
  year   = {2007},
  institution = { Harvard University }
  }
*** Comments
+ Some very similar ideas/concepts used here! Interesting :)
+ Importance sampling is the equivalent of likelihood weighting in Bayes
  networks, only done on programs themselves which allows more observations
  to be made. 
+ Claim: Vastly superior to rejection sampling
+ First simple approach:
  - In case patterns, check to see which patterns are non-inconsistent doing 
    minimal amount of work (no lets, nested distributions or function calls)
  - Very similar to my idea about handling cases (dysjunctions) by a "short
    introspection"
+ Improvement: Evidence Pushing
  - It essentially amounts to propagating information into paths in 
    which they are correct (if x then y else z, knows x is true in y0
+ Conditional Checking: like the first approach only for conditionals.
+ Delayed evaluation:
  - They delay sampling of a variable until they reach a let (pretty
    arbitrary as a choice and probably unnecessary in most cases, but
    reasonable) 
+ Targeted sampling: 
  - Allow substructures to be evaluated separately (ie. can sample the first
    component of a tuple instead of the whole thing)
  - The reason they have this is because their tuples are evaluated as a
    whole in paraller
** DONE Sampling via Program Analysis [ChagantyAISTATS13]
*** bib
@Inproceedings {ChagantyAISTATS13,
author       = {Arun T. Chaganty and Aditya V. Nori and Sriram K. Rajamani},
booktitle    = {Artificial Intelligence and Statistics (AISTATS)},
shortbooktitle = {AISTATS},
month        = {April},
title        = {Efficiently Sampling Probabilistic Programs via Program Analysis},
url          = {http://research.microsoft.com/apps/pubs/default.aspx?id=183833},
year         = {2013},
}
*** Comments
+ Link between Probabilistic sampling and symbolic execution!
+ Aim to do more efficient sampling using program analysis
+ Use for estimation of probabilities in prob programs.

+ QI algorithm:
  - First create a collection of all straight paths in a program 
    - If there are too many, user can set a bound
  - For each path provide two estimations based on Dijkstra's weakest
    preconditions:
    - the probability this path is executed
    - the expected value of this program path (computed by sampling 
      a possibly user bound number of samples)
  - Weigh the average amongst all paths
+ Explore algorithm: 
  - Essentially a simple BFS on the space of program paths
+ Estimation
  - Calculate weakest preconditions
  - Use them to generate a number of samples
+ Seems to work great for finite number of paths or programs whose paths can
  be "omitted"
