** DONE Survey [Jaffar_constraintlogic]
*** bib
@MISC{Jaffar_constraintlogic,
    author = {Joxan Jaffar and Michael J. Maher},
    title = {Constraint Logic Programming: A Survey},
    year = {},
    url = {http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.25.8566&rep=rep1&type=pdf}
}
*** Comments
+ CLP is more than just LP on steroids. Fundamentally different
  - LP doesn't deal with constraints as constraints
  - Could infinitely regress even if something is clearly unsatisfiable
  - Get CLP by meta-level programming adding pre's and post's in LP

+ Semantics: class of languages CLP(X)
  - X := (Σ, D, L, T) 
    - Σ := signature (set of functional/predicate symbols with arities)
    - D := Σ-structure (set + assignment of "meaning" to Σ)
    - L := class of expressable constraints
    - T := Axiomatization of (properties of) D
  - Prolog is CLP over finite trees
    - D <- set of finite trees where 
      * Labeled nodes by constants/function symbols
      * #children = arity 
      * ordered children
    - D interprets function symbols as (appropriate) tree constructors
    - Constraints are equations between terms
    - Also called: *Herbrand constraint domain*
  - CLP(FD) - finite domain. Used in CHIP amongst others.
    Integers with intervals and usual ops.
  - Solution compact domains:
    * Every element can be constructed by constraint conjunctions
    * Every elem in complement by dysjunctions
  - Independence of negative constraints: 
    Conjunction of positive and negative constraint is incosistent 
    <-> Conjunction of positive and ONE negative from above is inconsistent
  - Clark Completion: 
    Get all rules [p(x) <- Bi] and create \forall x, p(x) <-> \/ [\ex yi bi]
  - Some more models (logical, fixpoint and theory equivalences)
  - Operational Semantics:
    * Top-down:
      + Transition system on states <A,C,S>.
        A : multiset on atoms + constraints
        C + S : (constraint store) multiset of constraints
        C is awake - S is asleep
      + <A U a, C, S > ->r <A U B, C, S U (a=h)> 
        if h <- B and a,h share pred symbol, r for resolution
      + Allow (sometimes partial) consistency checks on C
      + Allow infering constraints (relaxation on (C,S)), (C,S) <-> (C', S')
      + QuickChecking := apply constistency + infer after each
        resolution/constraint intro step
    * Bottom-up: (database applications)
      + Forward reasoning checking subsumption (NP-Hard if non negative
        independence)
  - Extensions: 
    + Allow more information extracting
    + Play with rule application order
    + Add extra complex constraints
    + For dysjunctions one can use things like convex hulls to approximate
    + User-defined constraints
    + All LP negation variants can be ported here
    + Solution ordering 


+ Implementation
  * Incrementality
    - Incrementality is very important (and we didn't have it in the refiners
      work!)
    * Satisfiability
      - Represent constraints in a "solved form". One is *solution forms*
      - Solution forms are a format in which the set of all solutions of the
        constraints is evident
      - simple algo: Given C and new c, get substitution from C, apply it to c, 
        rewrite cθ to solution form (detecting unsat), sub in C, add in C.
    * Entailment
      - Given C and G (guards), where no constraint in G is entailed by C, find
        G1 < G s.t.  G1 containes constrained entailed by C ^ c 
      - Incrementality of this based upon ignoring non-entailed constraints
    * Projection 
      - Given target vars xs and constraints C(xs,ys) present solutions as
        \exists ys, C(xs,ys) in the most "usable" form
      - Mostly domain specific
        + For finite trees, it is the substitution obtained by the most 
          general unifier
    * Backtracking
      - Need to trail expressions, not just variables alone. This makes the
        problem MUCH more expensive in general than LP
      - Time stamps are used to avoid repeated trailing 
      - Reconstructions may sometimes be better than keeping extra info

  * Inference engine
    - Determine when to wake up a delayed goal or asleep constraint
      -> Activate when guard constraint is entailed by the store
    - Wakeup systems: 
      - p($1,..$n) /\ C
      - Wakeup degree is subset of p constraints
      - Wakeup system is wakeup degrees + transition automaton with
        wakeup conditions
    - Index structure mapping delayed constraint to occurence nodes DW-list
      Occ nodes points to a stack elt containing a delayed constraint
      + Delay: 
        Push C on stack and create appropriate dlists
      + Entailment:
        * Find all guards implied by new constraint (c)
        * For each DW-list and each constraint C = p(...)/\C', 
          delete all occ nodes pointing to C, push C'' = p(...)/\C'/\c
          with backpointers to C and construct new DW-lists
      + Backtracking:
        * Pop off the stack
        * For each backpointed C', act is if it was just pushed

  * Abstract Machine
    + Specialized constraint instructions for cases:
      - Add constraint, no sat check
      - Don't add constraint, sat check
      - Add and sat check, but not used later
    + Useful for optimizations


+ Applications
  - Specification Language
    * Not too close to our context
      - Circuit description/synthesis
      - Options trading
      - Temporal reasoning
  - Combinatorial Search Problems
    * Look into Hentenryck paper for intro
    * The reason to get into CLP in the first place
    * NP-Hard -> Partial Solvers
    * Issues:
      - Completeness vs efficiency
      - Redundant constraints
      - ORDER of constraints
      - Order of enumeration (less important for us?)
    * Some space for user ingenuity in the above 
      (eg. using special predicates)
    * Applications to other "hard" problems (eg. scheduling)
    * No mention of testing except for 
      "Support of CLP in Telecom Protocol Tests"
        
