  bibsource = {dblp computer science bibliography, http://dblp.org}
}
*** Comments
+ Goal : Solve constraint satisfaction problems on FINITE domains
- NP-complete
- Backtracking search is a reasonable way to go
- Arc (and path) consistency help decrease the search space
- They show an (optimal) algorithm (AC-4) which is O(ea^2), e 
  being the number of arcs (constraints) and a being the size of 
  the largest domain.
- The algorithm is fairly straightforward:
  + Go through all constraints (Cij) once, calculating the 
    subdomain of i that is inconsistent with all choices 
    in the domain of j given constraint Cij.
  + Remove these constraints from the domain Di and add them to 
    a queue Q.
  + While Q has elements, pick one (i,j,w) and:
    + Compute the values in Di that are no longer supported because 
      we removed the value w from Dj and remove them. If such values 
      exist, add them to Q
- Very dependent on the size of the domains. Good for numeric constraints. 
  If we add datatypes it blows up too fast. 
