*** Comments (Leo)
+ Addresses more constructs than Boltzmann samplers/grammar based generators
+ They use actual probability distributions (GeometricSamplers,
  DecaySamplers) and tune these parameters in their search
!! IDEA:
  The differential evolution process they use to tune their parameters could
  be used to tune local QC frequency choices given a fitness criterion based 
  on collect samples 
+ Their "specific properties" seem structural. Tuning parameters of a
  geometric distribution won't give you typed lambda terms, but it will give
  you trees of a certain height...
*** Comments (CH)
+ related to what we want on the parameter optimization side
+ they describe a GodelTest Ruby implementation using FeldtRuby::Optimize
  - GodelTest code doesn't seem available though, only FeldtRuby
    + he has something for Julia: https://github.com/robertfeldt/AutoTest.jl
      https://github.com/robertfeldt/InfoTheory.jl/blob/master/test/minitest.jl
  - they work in the OOP setting, which might explain why their work
    is not very well known in the FP community
  - they use meta-programming (which Ruby seems very good at), but
    this does not seem conceptually important, it's just glue
  - Li-yao has already reproduced (all?) their experiments
    + his experiments showed some strange generation strategies that
      seem only possible for arbitrary-branching trees
+ they distinguish between 4 kinds of choice points
  - m+, m*, choose_int, and "choose from methods with the same name"
  - the choice model provides integers which mean different things:
    + for m+ and m* - the number of iterations
    + for choose_int - the actual generated integer
    + "methods" - the overloaded method index to be called
  - in QC all low-level "choice points" could be of the form
    choose_int, but we can imagine something more high-level
+ their largest(!) example in QC syntax:
    import Test.QuickCheck
    genExp n =
       oneof $ [show `fmap` (choose (0,10) :: Gen Int)] ++
               [do
                 e1 <- genExp (n-1)
                 o <- elements ["+", "-"]
                 e2 <- genExp (n-1)
                 return $ "(" ++ e1 ++ o ++ e2 ++ ")" | n > 0]
    gen = listOf (genExp 7)
+ in this paper they assume independent choice points
+ more powerful than just choosing numeric weights
  - they show decay sampler, parameterized by recursion depth
    + this could probably remove the need to explicitly keep track of
      the size of expressions in the generator (even in their simple one)
+ experiments generating arbitrarily branching trees
  - they simultaneously optimize both size and height
  - more than what Bolzmann samplers can do, but still unimpressive
  - mutation or coverage experiments would seem better suited at
    testing the limits of what they can do

