  url       = {http://www-ps.informatik.uni-kiel.de/~sebf/pub/ppdp07.html},
}
*** Comments:
+ Goal: White box testing for functional Logic Programming (Curry)
+ Curry is like Haskell with *partial data structures* and different evaluation
  mechanism 
+ Evaluation strategies are:
  - Needed narrowing <-> lazy evaluation
  - Residuation <-> suspended computation until other comps give a value to a
    variable
+ Their aim is to minimize testing effort with respect to coverage criteria
+ I don't like the claim "Remaining errors can be eliminated eg. by black box
  testing". If white box testing can't find at least all the errors that black 
  box can, then what's the point?
+ Their global branch coverage criterion is very strong (including *actually*
  unreachable code in some cases)
+ Their function coverage seems weak - waiting for section 5.
+ For generation, they use the narrowing-based search mechanism of Curry
  (logic programming) to enumerate inputs-solutions, adding the possibility of 
  limiting generation by depth, number of tests. They also require BFS-like
  search for better results.
+ Then they REMOVE test cases to cover their criterion! (Also
  Set-Cover/NP-complete)
+ Allow the use of custom generators for preconditions (like unique :D )
+ Naive transformation: Rewrite of the program into a writer-like
  monad
+ Adoptation to preserve laziness: Store a Tree of information along with 
  every value. 
  - Root: Items that are covered to compute the HNF of the value
  - Subtree fore every argument of the head-constructor.
+ They have a formalization of their transformation.
!!! OVERALL:
 ++ More of a QC-on-steroids for Curry
 ++ No solving of the precondition problem (even with narrowing)
 ++ Interesting ideas that are close with our refiners work though:
  - Partial data structures
  - Residuation 

