    publisher = {ACM Press},
    volume = 47,
    number = 4,
    url = {https://www.informatik.uni-kiel.de/~mh/papers/JACM00.pdf},
    }
*** Comments
+ Introduces the notion of *needed* narrowing as an evaluation
  strategy for rewrite systems
+ Basically, it amounts to introducing in the context of rewrite systems the
  same notion of *need* that laziness introduces in functional programming
+ Quite a bit of technical material to prove optimality of this strategy with
  respect to number of derivation steps.
+ Targets a subclass of rewrite systems that is said to "model the first-order
  component of functional languages like ML/Haskell" (which means, quite an
  interesting subclass)
+ The main idea is not to do rewrites that could be proved unnecessary later
  on and the key behind this is to not always use most general unifiers.
+ No mention of testing whatsoever, it would be interesting to see which paper 
  actually made the connection (Smallcheck/LazyCheck?)

