}
Implementation: http://www.cs.york.ac.uk/fp/smallcheck/

*** Comments
+ Systematic enumeration of small values compared to random generation of QC
+ Systematic approach with *Serial* typeclass, similar to Arbitrary
+ Can Handle existential properties which QC can't
+ Allows for some customization (playing with depth and filtering)
+ Lazy SmallCheck uses Haskell's laziness to avoid complete instantiation.
+ That allows them to prune the search space much faster
+ The order of premises is important, that's why they introduce Parallel
  conjunction. It allows for using laziness in both sides of an &&, greatly 
  reducing the thought burden on the programmer and improving performance
  slightly. However, it might expose partiality of the second conjunct leading
  to wrong behavior.
+ For inputs without laziness, LazyCheck can be worse than SmallCheck!
+ In the Implementation they use the notion of paths (the paths of the *Needed
  Narrowing Strategy* paper) to track which uninstantiated variable needs
  further instantiation.
+ Very pretty implementation! Haskell is awesome :)
+ Small experimentation, not systematic in counterexample generation. Still,
  it proves the point that for properties with lazy preconditions, LazyCheck
  does WAY better than out-of-the-box SmallCheck/QuickCheck
+ Residuation is related to the parallel conjunction (suspended computation)
+ "Complementary approaches"

