*** Comments
+ Goal: Combine testing and proving in the same language
- They added a quickCheck like tool in Agda and specifically in 
  Agda/Alfa (Alfa is a window manager)
- As a QuickCheck clone, it looks pretty good. Allows writing 
  generators in Agda syntax and has great integration with the 
  proof assistant, allowing you to test subgoals during the proof.
- They claim (correctly) that one can prove surjectivity (completeness) 
  for constructors and advocate that it is a great advantage of writing 
  generators in Agda (instead eg. of Haskell). However, when 
  saying they don't show any such proof of surjectivity. To prove things 
  like: 
    
   (lb, ub :: Nat) -> T (lb < ub) -> 
   (t      :: BT ) -> T (isBST lb ub t) -> 
   (sig {seed :: BT; prf :: T (genBST lb ub seed) = t } 
  
  one must effectively reverse the generator to produce a seed witness for 
  an arbitrary BinaryTree t.. It doesn't seem like something done easily 
  without a framework support like Zoe's...
  - CH: Their proof is still very simple, see pg 17 of Chapter 1 of [Haiyan03]
- As Catalin had asked, how do they deal with infinite types (e.g. lists?)
- They present a couple of case studies that feel more like experience
  reports. They show how testing can complement proving quite effectively.
- The intrinsic AVL discussions doesn't feel like adding anything to the
  paper.

+++ This is much more a "Testing can Help Proving" paper than a 
  "We can prove QuickCheck/Generators Correct" paper. Proving surjectivity 
  is a minor point in favor of combining, but there is no real support 
  for it. 

