*** Comments 
!! Only read Testing-related chapter of thesis and related work
!! The following is with regard to the testing chapter only
+ Goal: Support dependently typed programming/proving using testing
+ Claim: They created a QC-like tool for Coq to be used either automatically 
  in an ACL2-like style for proving non-theorems in generalization efforts 
  or manually to disprove (possibly faulty) subgoals
+ The class of testable properties (Prop though!) is very small: 
  + True, False, /\, \/, ->, ~, = (for ground terms) , < and > for nat.
  + No existentials (expected), but also no foralls, functions. 
  + ie. should only be used after everyhting has been introduced?
+ Expect manual instantiation of types for polymorphic arguments 
  (command available for user)
+ Sized, automatic generation for inductively defined types WITH base
  constructors. For zero size, choose only base constructors.
  For non-zero, pick any constructor and recurse cutting the size in half. 
  This only works well on binary trees. For lists, only very small ones are
  generated. For ternary tress (or similar), we have a blow-up.
--- No support for manual, handwritten generators --- 
+ Small value to satisfy sideconditions - counteract lack of shrinking
+ Interesting approach to function generation: 
  - User must supply a list of functions to choose from
  - Probably leeds to more interesting functions than CoArbitrary...
  - More burden for the user not necessarily bad if it leads to better 
    testing (IMO)
+ Run INSIDE Coq. (200 * 200 nat takes 0.35 secs...). That leads them to 
  generate only small terms
